hor thanks the staff for their mapping effort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as the Framework used by the author cannot be subjectively mapped onto the quest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ionnaire. </span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Part Three: </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Identification</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> and analysing Hazards</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> Using System for Investigation of Railway Interfaces (SIRI)</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">US </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ollar billionaire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as per Forbes magazine 2012 data </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is approximately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is 37</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The population of the UK is around 63.23 million. The probability of a finding dollar bil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lionaire is roughly five parts by million. In a more precise and accurate terms, the figure is worked out to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.85165E-06</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The probability of a cyclist killed at level crossing is (assuming the only cyclist killed at a level crossing is =1/63.23 million or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roughly one part per ten million. The probability of cyclist being killed at a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">train </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">level crossing is more unlikely than the probability of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">US </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dollar billionaire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The probability of cyclist being killed on London Street and the probability of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a US dollar billionaire are of similar magnitude of probabilities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, this feature of similarity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of probabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not induce similar intuitions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The difference in intuitions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arising from consideration of these scenarios and their role on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behavi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our is discussed later in the text. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Now, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">following the work of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sychologists like Nobel Laureate Daniel Kahnem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Amos Tversky and Prospect Theory they advance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, author</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> judges </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the situations as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reflecting gambling tendency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> situations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Because </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> involving writing bestselling novels or crossing level crossing when train is coming </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involve risk taking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> involving very low probabilities of success</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(pp317)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Kahneman, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Jonathan Haidt, a psychologist cited by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Daniel Kahnemen expressed this tendency by the following saying, “emotional tail wags the rational dog”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">type of think</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing about situations involving emotions that affect risk is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">summarised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by author </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as perceptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of harm being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more important than act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ual harm. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This type of thinking is not new. Roman Emperor, Marcus Aurelius (121-180 AD) counselled that perceptions of harm are more dangerous. Because whatever choices we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make Nature is divine and headed in a certain direction is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the core idea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at the hear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t of the Stoic philosophy</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Now, Let us consider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hypothetical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scenario: s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uppose some dark night a policeman walks down a street, apparently deserted; but suddenly he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hears a burglar alarm, looks across the street, and sees a jewellery store with a brok</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en window. Then</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a gentleman wearing a mask comes crawling out through the broken window, carrying a bag which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">turns out to be full of expensive jewellery. The policeman doesn't hesitate at all in deciding that this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gentleman is dishonest. But by what </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reasoning process does he arrive at this conclusion</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> What is the probability that this policeman is in error? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The idea of a US dollar billionaire in the UK conjures up image of one who is working very hard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by being enterprising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, striving to help the eco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nomy by employing lot of people and being a useful member of society.  However, UK billionaire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">writer is a different</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual from this description </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is told as rags-to riches story</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the idea of a cyclist dodging a train at a level crossing</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  inv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">okes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a different kind of feeling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Members of the British Transport Police are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reportedly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hunting for the lone woman cy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clist who jumped red lights but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">narrowly escaped death. Author wishes to thank God for the miraculous save.  Whereas members of the Brit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ish Transport </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Police, author speculates, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may admire imagination of the writer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of Harry Potter Book </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when watching the Harry Potter film</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the TV or at a theatre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Author speculates that members of the British Transport Police do not comprehend the idea of A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ristotelian</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (intuitive) physics in the theatre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">scenario </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Penrose, 2004)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Reason, 1990)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The idea of criminalising the activity of jumping red lights may be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> good option for policing activity at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> junctions where likelihood of traffic conflicts may arise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">escaping the conflicts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by jumping </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">may be good option </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for the cycling activity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as som</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e of the Submissions attest to. Whereas criminalising </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stealing of jewellery is reasonable policing ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ivity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When thinking about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such tragic cases involving death</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it is not normally recognised that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the idea of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ime is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">associated with the changes of states</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and focal attention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of a living being. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This association of Time and human experience is known </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as Entropy</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Expressed in an informal manner, entropy is a physically perceptible process when a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rubber band is stretched, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n egg is dropped onto a floor, a car crashes into a lamp post or a cyclist is struck by a train or another</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> road vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These one w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ay processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are studied in physics as involving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a quantity known as Entropy. The resulting dis-order can never be decreased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ir-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reversible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In other words, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">author argues that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">entropy and unsafety are identical concepts and are state properties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> like s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">weetness is of sugar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and does not belong to its constituents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Walker, 2008)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Ashby, 1957)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In other words, an individual alone cannot be considered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the explanation but must involve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">whole </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-technical</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">system.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A cyclist, car driver, train driver, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pilot may bring about harm to themselves and others because they may lack skills in riding a by-cycle, driving a car or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">driving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a train or piloting an aircraft</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ut under the conditions of modern </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> century society, it is a rarity that people learn to do things by themselves without aid or help from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> others. Even learning from others </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">involves in these circumstances engaging with a manufactured (or programmed) object.  Production of these objects r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">equire making plans, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">carrying out the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">produce, assemble , market and utilise them. Rules and regulations regulating the activity of individuals, on the job-training, type of school education and family influence are some of the factors shapin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g the behaviour of the individual. Therefore, when thinking about such tragic situations, we employ what is known as Systems Thinking to prevent re-occurrence of tragic situations by learning about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">root causal factors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and acting upon them</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Travel be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">haviour of cyclists was discussed in a latest academic publication</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, there is another</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> academic research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that has been useful to the author can be accessed from here</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> From these documents, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">author has learnt </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is no linear relationship that can be inferred between cycling activity and exposure to hazard at the level crossing that can be used as an indicator of safety. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Author agrees to the two proposition(s) advanced by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Nobel Laureate Daniel Kahneman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Kahneman, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. First, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">domain experts are hostages to emotional, cognitive and social factors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and failure to acknowledge their ignorance is encouraged by their clients.  Second, certain occupations need high resilience in the wak</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e of high failure rates. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In conclusion, economists who believe in the rational model of behaviour have driven out rational engineers from system safety management practice area and allowed their place to be taken by safety assurance providers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach to safety assurance does not delve into root causes nor is able to apply laws of probability correctly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(A.G.Hessami, 2012)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This leads to a dis-benefit to the society is that it pays the costs of harm directly. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Hazar</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">d Identification by Partial Hypothetical HAZOP Study: </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The text in this section presents the hazard model in the form of HAZOP</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, EBTA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">worksheets in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tabular form to represent the hazard faced by a cyclist, its causes and consequences as a desktop study.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">Table </span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">: Hypothetical Partial HAZOP study (Operating and Support Hazop Study) </span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:473.7pt"><tr><td colspan="2" style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:55.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Drawing Number</span></p></td><td colspan="8" style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:418.6