:70.85pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Loss of life of a cyclist </span></p></th><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regulation and control of train movements Less Than Adequate ( LTA)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Segregating of traffic streams LTA( civil engineers do not wish to construct bridge) </span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The application of UK Best Practice for Risk Management LTA</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">European Railway Agency is of the firm opinion that Common Safety Indicator of fatalities per activity is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">good indicator of safety performance whereas empirical data analysis does not show any kind of linear relationship</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Lack of Competence on the part of European Railway Agency in the application of System Thinking Approach to Safety </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as directed by EU Saf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ety Directive (2004/2009) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is self –evident from the careful reading of the information listed on their website. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Even UK HSE Reducing Risk and Protecting People suffers from this cognitive error</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Generation of collision(hazard)  scenarios during the scheme planning stages LTA( </span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Specification of train regulation and control schemes LTA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(RSSB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Railway Group Standards are the ORR basis for Network Rail’s Operating License)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The Railway Group Standar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ds do not specify conditions that may manifest hazards for the duty-holders. </span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Accident Investigation techniques LTA (RAIB use of Haddon type of information on flow of sequence of events during pre and post-accident stages does not lead to James Reason’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Model). </span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Representations to generate and capture hazard scenarios LTA ( ORR does not use any information to inform itself of the hazard scenarios) </span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Comprehension of systemic causal factors LTA (Network Rail Level Crossing Risk Assessment Mod</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">el does </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not capture engineering and management errors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span></p></th></tr><tr><th style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:333.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Awareness of Systemic Errors (biases) LTA ( Network Rail Level Crossing Risk Assessment Model does not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any branch to model them) Risk scoring does not help hazard causal factors. </span></p></th></tr></thead></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the question of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">safety budget for eliminating risk from level crossings, Nobel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Laureate Daniel Kahneman hypothetical argument </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">against precautionary principle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is difficult to sustain as the budget of £9 billion is insignificant in comparison to other amounts of £80 billion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Finance Loan Schemes to support house buying activity</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Nobel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Laureate Daniel Kahneman does agree that people do not wish to trade minute increase in risk to their health of their near and dear ones (pp350/351)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Kahneman, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Management Oversight and Risk Tree Work sheet is not applied in this Case Study as author earlier submission to the Transport Committee on the theme of Cycling Safety and Safety at Level Crossings have addressed the method already. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Application of Management Oversight and Risk Tree Worksheet as part of SIRI Framework to the Case Studies of Challenger Accident, Japanese Nuclear Accident, and Herefordshire Level Crossing Accidents show that dependability type of approach applied by auto</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mation engineers and managers are not useful for identifying hazards and their elimination. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The combination of latent failures in understanding has been listed in this accident case study as well. By correcting these level of safety may improve. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Bibliogr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">aphy</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some of the references that guided author’s thinking are listed here. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A.G.Hessami, 2012. </span><span style="font